<DOC><DOCNO> AP880524-0112 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1114EDT</FILEID><FIRST>d a PM-BRF--UAW-JaiAlai     05-24 0137</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--UAW-Jai Alai,0139</SECOND><HEAD>Jai Alai Association Leaders Recommend Joining UAW</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: Player's in lede is cq.</NOTE><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Leaders of the striking International Jai AlaiPlayer's Association have recommended its members join the UnitedAuto Workers union.   The 500-member association is expected to vote on the questionwithin 10 days, UAW officials said Monday. A yes vote would markthe first time a professional athletic association has joined ageneral membership union.   The player's association last month struck 14 arenas in Florida,Connecticut and Rhode Island, alleging unfair labor practicesconcerning contract negotiations and pensions.   The UAW is taking the association's complaints before theNational Labor Relations Board, said UAW Region 9a spokesman HenryMurray.   The UAW, which has about 1 million members, representsautoworkers, engineers, doctors, lawyers, aircraft workers,shoemakers, journalists and clerical employees.</TEXT></DOC>